<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870212-0175 </DOCNO><HL> Netherlands Curbs ForecastFor 1987 Current Account</HL><DD> 02/12/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> EUROPMONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON) </IN><DATELINE> THE HAGUE, the Netherlands  </DATELINE><TEXT>    The Dutch government, citingexpectations of a continued weak dollar and higher oilprices, sharply reduced its forecast for the 1987current-account surplus.   In a preliminary review of economic trends for this year, the government projected a surplus equivalent to $3.66 billion, down from the $6.35 billion surplus projected last September. In 1986, the surplus on the current account, which comprises trade in goods and services as well as some unilateral transfers, was $7.08 billion. All figures are converted at the guilder's current rate.    The trade surplus was forecast to narrow to $976 million this year from $4.63 billion in 1986.    The government kept unchanged at 2% its forecast for economic growth this year. That would be up from 1986's 1.5% expansion. </TEXT></DOC>